Vladimir Putin and the Risk of a Third World War
San Francisco — On February 24, Russia's invasion of Ukraine marked the beginning of a third world war that could potentially destroy our civilization.
Before the invasion, Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping had a lengthy meeting on February 4 — the day marking the beginning of China's Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympic Games.
After the meeting, the two released a carefully drafted, 5,000-word document announcing the establishment of a close partnership between the two countries.
This document is stronger than any treaty and certainly requires detailed negotiations in advance.
I was shocked that Xi seemed to have fully entrusted Putin with launching the invasion and war in Ukraine.
He believed that the confirmation of his becoming a lifelong ruler this下半年 is merely a formality, and he was definitely confident about it.
After concentrating all power in his own hands, Xi carefully planned a scheme to elevate himself to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
With the support of Xi, Putin set about realizing his lifelong dream in an incredibly brutal manner.
At nearly 70, Putin feels that if he wants to leave a significant mark in Russian history, it's either now or never.
But his view of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
He seems to think that the Russian people need a Tsar who can be blindly followed.
This system is diametrically opposed to a democratic society, and this vision has distorted the "soul" of the Russian people, who are emotionally and sentimentally exaggerated.
In my childhood, I had a lot of contact with Russian soldiers who occupied Hungary in 1945.
I know that if you ask them, they will share their last piece of bread with you.
Later, in the early 1980s, I launched what I call my political philanthropy.
At first, I established a foundation in my home country, Hungary, and later I actively participated in activities that contributed to the dissolution of the Soviet Empire.
By the time Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, this process of disintegration had already begun.
I also established a foundation in Russia, and later, in each of the newly independent republics.
In Ukraine, I founded a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984 and became the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (I closed the foundation in 1989, shortly after the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't personally know Putin, but I have been closely following his rise and fully understand his ruthless personality.
He reduced Chechnya's capital, Grozny, to rubble, and now he threatens to do the same to Ukraine's capital, Kyiv.
Putin was once a shrewd KGB agent, but he has seemed to change recently.
He seems to have lost touch with reality because he has formed a fixed notion.
There's no doubt that he misjudged the situation in Ukraine.
He had assumed that the Ukrainian-speaking Ukrainians would welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but the reality proved that they were no different from the Ukrainian-speaking population.
Faced with the seemingly one-sided possibility, the Ukrainian people still carried out an incredibly brave resistance.
In July 2021, Putin published a long article stating that Russians and Ukrainians are actually one nation, and that Ukrainians have been misled by new Nazi agitators.
Since Kyiv is the original site of the Russian Orthodox Church, the first part of his argument is not without historical basis.
But in the content of Part 2, it was Putin who was misled.
He should have known the facts more clearly.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the Euromaidan protests that erupted in 2014.
The incident in 2014 made him very angry.
But when ordered to attack their Ukrainian brothers, the Russian army performed poorly.
The deep-rooted corruption within the Ministry of Defense also played a significant role in this poor performance.
But Putin not only didn't blame himself, but seemed to have gone mad.
He has resolved to punish Ukraine for opposing him, and his actions seem to be unconstrained.
He threw the entire Russian army into battle and disregarded all the rules of warfare, especially the indiscriminate bombing of civilian populations.
Many hospitals were attacked, and the power grid that supplies electricity to the Chernobyl Nuclear Power Plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) was also damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, as many as 400,000 people have had no water or food in the past week.
Russia is very likely to lose this war.
Both the United States and the European Union are supplying Ukraine with defensive weapons while also trying to purchase Russian-made MiG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to operate.
These could change the entire situation.
No matter the outcome, Putin has created miracles in strengthening Europe's resolve and unity.
At the same time, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is having an affair.
On March 8, after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi reaffirmed that Sino-Russian friendship remains "as firm as a rock," President Xi Jinping called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz, expressing his support for their peacekeeping efforts.
To avoid a humanitarian crisis, he hopes to exercise maximum restraint during the war.
It remains uncertain whether Putin will yield to Xi's intentions.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi are removed from power before they destroy our civilization.
